   {:created-at #inst "2026-04-28T08:00:00.000-00:00",
    :abstract
    "Filesystem and code-editing primitives for the SCI sandbox: read,\nlist, search, and patch files. Bound under the `vis` alias as\n`vis/cat`, `vis/ls`, `vis/rg` (RE2/J, ReDoS-safe regex search), and\n`vis/patch` (path+search+replace, marker-delimited SEARCH/REPLACE,\nmulti-edit vector, or Codex `*** Begin Patch` payload). Default\ntoolbelt the agent reaches for in nearly every coding task.",
    :content
    "\n# Common operations extension\n\nPackage: `com.blockether/vis-common-operations`. Source:\n`extensions/vis-common-operations/`. Canonical location: inlined\nunder `[vis :docs \"README.md\"]` in `META-INF/vis-extension/vis.edn`\n(shipped in the jar). The LLM reads it via\n`(meta/extension-readme 'vis)` from inside `:code`.\n\nFilesystem and code-editing primitives the agent reaches for in\nnearly every task. Symbols bind under the `vis` alias inside the SCI\nsandbox; the underlying namespace alias is `vis.ext.tools`.\n\nAdd the jar to the classpath, or list\n`com.blockether/vis-common-operations` in your `deps.edn`, to enable\nit. The CLI's default `:vis` alias already wires it in for daily\nagent runs.\n\n## Read a file\n\nCall: `(vis/cat path)` or `(vis/cat path opts)`. Returns the file\ncontents along with size and line count. The opts MAP supports paging\nfor large files; see the symbol's `:examples` for the full form.\n\n```clojure\n(vis/cat \"deps.edn\")\n(vis/cat \"packages/vis-core/src/com/blockether/vis/core.clj\"\n         {:from-line 1 :to-line 80})\n```\n\n## List files and directories\n\nCall: `(vis/ls)` or `(vis/ls path opts)`. Returns a tree projection\ntrimmed to fit the current context budget; honors `.gitignore` and a\nconfigurable depth/limit.\n\n```clojure\n(vis/ls)\n(vis/ls \"packages\")\n(vis/ls \"extensions\" {:depth 2})\n```\n\n## Search files\n\nCall: `(vis/rg pattern)` or `(vis/rg pattern path opts)`. Linear-time\nregex search using RE2/J (ReDoS-safe). Returns hits as\n`{:path :line :match}` maps. Inside a Clojure string `\\|` is not a\nvalid escape — use bare `|` for regex alternation, or use a `#\"…\"`\nregex literal for complex patterns.\n\n```clojure\n(vis/rg \"TODO\")\n(vis/rg \"defn\" \"packages/vis-core/src\")\n(vis/rg #\"\\bdef(n|method)\\b\" \"src\")\n```\n\n## Patch a file\n\nCall: `(vis/patch ...)`. Unified patch tool that supports four input\nshapes:\n\n1. `(vis/patch path search replace)` — three-argument literal text\n   patch.\n2. `(vis/patch path \"<<<<<<< SEARCH\\n…\\n=======\\n…\\n>>>>>>> REPLACE\")` —\n   marker-delimited form. Robust against embedded quotes and brackets;\n   prefer this for multi-line or quote-heavy edits.\n3. `(vis/patch [{:path :search :replace} …])` — vector of edits, each\n   applied in order.\n4. `(vis/patch \"*** Begin Patch\\n…\\n*** End Patch\")` — Codex-style\n   payload.\n\nWhen a SEARCH block fails to match exactly, the error includes a\n`:near-match` hint when the only difference is leading whitespace, so\nyou can re-emit a corrected SEARCH block on the next iteration without\nre-reading the whole file.\n\n```clojure\n(vis/patch \"src/auth.clj\" \"(defn login [user]\" \"(defn login [user opts]\")\n\n(vis/patch \"src/auth.clj\"\n  \"<<<<<<< SEARCH\n(defn login [user]\n  (verify user))\n=======\n(defn login [user opts]\n  (verify user opts))\n>>>>>>> REPLACE\")\n```\n\n## When to use it\n\n- Reading, listing, searching, or editing files inside the project the\n  agent is working on.\n- Multi-line edits where naive text replacement is fragile — use the\n  marker form of `vis/patch` rather than typing the search/replace\n  payload as Clojure strings.\n\n## When not to use it\n\n- Pure data transformations on already-loaded values; that's plain\n  Clojure inside the sandbox.\n- Cross-process work that needs a real shell. The extension is\n  filesystem-scoped on purpose.\n\n## Implementation notes\n\n- All four symbols are dispatched through the extension framework;\n  parse-error rescue lives at the symbol level (e.g. on `vis/rg`) so\n  the iteration loop only retries when the broken source actually\n  mentions the offending symbol.\n- `vis/rg` uses RE2/J (no backtracking, ReDoS-safe). `vis/cat` and\n  `vis/ls` are bounded and trim to fit the current context budget.\n- The extension owns no persistence state. Every call is pure with\n  respect to the runtime — the only side effects are file reads and\n  the explicit writes performed by `vis/patch`.\n",
